i am disappointed with their cha shu ramen - there is very little amount of bbq pork. will probably come back but will order another item on the menu. oh i tried the yakisoba it's just average nothing special.
I think it's average. Pricey for the food you get.
Pork sinigang and Sisig are the best! I will return!
The tip about sitting at the bar is spot on.
Kitchen is open until midnight!
Best place for fresh fruits and veggies. Always a crowd.
In the northwest corner. Small, but tasty!
The McDonald's here is 24 hours.
Best donuts. Delivered fresh early every morning.
The best orange chicken I have ever had!
If your breakfast comes with a biscuit you can get it with garavy!
Delicious nondairy options! I had the peach sorbet, irresistible! Plus super friendly-local atmosphere.
Dairy\/sugar\/gluten\/soy free!! It's cold, but amazing! Can be warmed with oatmeal for free before noon.
Sick venue.
$1 day on Monday. Double tag day on Tuesday.
Tickets can be bought at any register in concessions.
Have quite a few gluten-free choices.
Gluten-free teriyaki and sugar free stevi-yaki!
Everything is perfect. Thanks yelpers.
Busy as usual. Love it all!!!!  Me hungry
Always a favorite when in Phoenix
Love their Caesar salad, gyoza, free hot rolls...  And all their dishes.
Hmm. Univ of Phoenix
I like how the airport has plugs for phones here. Very thoughtful.
Quick flight but US air flight attendant kinda grouchy
Nice airport. Have TV by gate to watch Monday night football. Very considerate.
HB here I come.
Looks very Ono
Great fun at a very reasonable price to watch MLB.

Was recommended. Let's see if they better than the ones in Cali & Hawaii. But totally wrong. Made both my son & I bleed cuz both cut us. Never again. To top it off, they told us never to go back cuz I said we ate both bleeding.
Don't come here unless you feel like getting cut & paying for it. They cut both my son& I. I told them & they said don't come back. What?  Worst nail salon I ever been to. Never again.
Nice hotel. Worst service at restaurant ever. She sucks bad. Rude, inattentive, ridiculous.
Packed flight.
Packed!!!
Never been to a circle K. Interesting.
Pubic hair in bathroom to greet us. Not good. Fricken gross.
Gets go team USA.
OMG!  All done with Christmas. Killer deal but now pooped.
Yummy & spicy & super friendly service
Pure excellence at the Wynn everytime.
What a surprise. Healthy food in Phoenix?  Stoked!
I like this place. Close to everything. And nice gooey chewy cookies & ice cold water too. Very nice.
Nice place. Like it!
Picture perfect day. Great organic food.  Now baseball time!
Yelp recommended this place. So far so good.
So healthy
Nice place.
Best deals ever. Saved over $800. Do happy. Great service too.
Heard chocolate cake is fabulous. But I don't gots sweet tooth
Fun place.

First time eating Cambodian food ever. Good ratings. OMG!  So fricken delicious. Lemongrass soup with perfect flavor & meat was excellent.  Amoy fish awesome too but added red chili sauce. Perfect. Oh, grass jelly drink refreshing.
Which Vietnamese restaurant does not serve pho or rice after a certain hour?  This place. Never again. Also server was a smart ass.
Amazing Holy Shiitake pizza. Great beer selection. Terrific service.
Highest rating. Why not?
Looks fantastic
It's just ok. Salty shrimp gumbo soup.
omg!  yum
Not familiar with the menu but willing to try. Looks good tho
Kinda like Slaters 50\/50 in Arizona. Beach theme & lots TV & surfboards everywhere
If you are afraid to try, try anyway. You will leave refreshed & full of energy. I would come again anytime, anyday.
Super long wait but they text so that's awesome
Grand opening. Very nice Starbucks. Has FREE coffee & hot chocolate. FREE always excellent.
Japanese owned and mostly staffed by Japanese (incl. kitchen). Owner is from Hakata region. Tan tan men is peanut free for those with peanut allergies.

This place blows away all of its competitors for making the best Hong Kong street style egg shaped waffles (or eggettes, egg puffs, whatever people are calling them these days) - crispy on the outside, moist and airy on the inside, just like how they were made years ago when I was a child growing up in HK. One order takes at least twice as long as its competitors, but so worth the wait, and the best I've had in at least the last 10 years!
Second time here since we arrived last Saturday. My parents took me here 3 years ago when I came to TO for a visit. It's my favorite dim sum place in the GTA and surrounding areas.

3rd time here for dim sum in less than a week!  Regular price if you order after 10:45 am ($2.8 for small, $3.8 for medium, $4.9 for large, etc.). All dishes $2.8 if you order before 10:45 am, although some specialty varieties are not available before 10:45 am.
Early bird specials begin at 9:00 a.m. and end at 10:45 a.m. (last call to submit order) daily. Slight price hike for early bird specials from $3 to $3.10 per dish in effect 2 weeks ago.

This was my overall favorite dim sum spot in the GTA and York Region areas for a number of years a few years back. It was just ok the last time I went (July 2015). My family in Toronto, regulars for years since it opened, have stopped going altogether because of a steep decline in food taste and quality since the former chef's departure.
$6.25 for a "large" passionfruit tea with lychee jelly.  The Canadian "large" seems more like an American "regular" cup.  Makes Tea Station and Cha for Tea prices seem cheap...really cheap....

One of my favorite places for HK style breakfasts. Recommended items include HK cafe staples such as pineapple buns served warm with butter on the side, "piggy buns" (rolls) served toasted with butter and condensed milk, and HK style milk tea.
Craving for some curry fish balls. This place makes really tasty curry fish balls, authentic Hong Kong style, @ $3.50 for 10 pieces.
This was Julian's favorite when he was Bethany's age. Time flies....

Somehow my sis and I managed to spend a couple of hours shopping here, for stuff we did not really need. It's kind of like the Daiso stores in Cali, except the couple of bucks section is smaller and not very impressive, but the regular section has some cute plush toys (Rilakkuma, et al.), Re-Ment collectibles, Hello Kitty stationery, other licensed products, gadgets, and a lot of other cute things you don't need but you will buy anyway.

Kosher Sobey's in a predominantly Jewish surburb. Shopping for sours (pickles) and other Jewish groceries. We found whole (as opposed to medium) granulated kasha - something not available at the local grocery store where we live in southern California.

Montreal style Jewish deli diner with authentic Montreal smoked meat sandwiches that is not quite kosher (noticed some meat dishes served with dairy).  Expect a wait unless you go during the off-peak lunch and dinner hours.
Deli style mustard (Woeber's Spicy Brown Mustard and Nance's Sharp & Creamy) available by request, in addition to non-deli style French's yellow mustard on tables.

As of my last trip in October (2014), this has overtaken Spring Villa's No. 1 spot for my overall favorite dim sum spot in Toronto\/York regions. Favorites here include steamed taro and oysters, steamed rrice noodle rolls with avocado and eel, steamed mushroom and vegetable bean curd sheet rolls. Selection of vegetarian dim sum varieties is pretty good.

According to my parents (since I didn't pay), who are regulars at Spring Villa (Markham), Elegance (Markham) and Casa Imperial (Scarborough), the cost of dim sum here, even after the 10% late bird special, is more costly than the mid-price dim sum restaurants such as Ginger & Onion (Scarborough) but quality is much lower.

Amazing fish buns (my opinion) and mutton rolls (Sri Lankan friend's opinion) and possibly the best in the area. High quality Sri Lankan baked goods, reasonable prices, clean premises, friendly and efficient service - what more can you ask for?
Bubble gum swirl ice cream (with pieces of bubble gum in the ice cream) for the kids!!
Peking duck dinner tonight! Also having double boiled winter melon soup, which must be pre-ordered 2 days in advance.

Early dim sum before our road trip to Blue Mountain! Order by 11:30 am (Mondays through Saurdays only) and pay only $2.5 for all small, medium and large dim sim varieties. One of the better places for creative dim sum of high quality.
Must trys include Peking duck and double boiled winter melon soup, which must be ordered in advance.

Dinners and banquets are better than dim sum in general, especially if you arrange for the banquet through Mandy the manager. Early bird dim sum and afternoon tea pricing is $2.80 for all varieties, though selection is smaller than regular push cart dim sum between the hours of 11:00 a.m. and 2:00 p.m. (S: $2.80, M: $3.80, L: $4.80, XL: $5.80).
Way better selection for girls sizes 8-12 than its few stores in the U.S. More back to school clothes for my 8 year old.
Stopping for iced coffee for the adults and timbits for the kids.

Getting the Wii Sports, extra controller and nunchuck for my parents who fell in love with the game on the northern European cruise they took in June. U.S. Best Buy Rewards will not work here (not a surprise, right?!).
Hole-in-the-wall Hong Kong style cafe.  Portions are large and prices are cheap but quality is not so great.

The name (Sam Woo) is the same as those in the U.S. but the taste is so much better in TO, esp. if you are used to Hong Kong standards. Afternoon specials range from $4.50-$6.50 and all come with a drink (hot coffee or HK milk tea); add $0.75 for iced coffee\/HK milk tea).

Eat-in only afternoon specials from 2:30 p.m. to 5:30 p.m. in three price categories ($4.5, $5.5 and $6.5).  All specials with complimentary hot tea or coffee (incl. HK milk tea), $0.75 extra to substitute for an iced beverage.
This little hole-in-the-wall joint serves authentic Sri Lankan Jaffna Tamil food. The Friday vegetarian specials are highly recommended (with high praises from even my native Sri Lankan friend).

Dinner with mom and uncle at mom's favorite restaurant. I don't eat pork but my dad (of Hakka origin), mom and sister, who are regulars here, give their votes to this restaurant for having the best Hakka braised pork belly (惠州梅菜扣肉) in town. My favorites here include dried radish and whitebait fish omelette (白飯魚菜甫煎蛋), double steamed winter melon soup and the "bird's nest" dishes with "nests" made of deep fried shredded taro.

The crispy skin boneless chicken stuffed with Chinese sausage and dried shrimp sticky rice (糯米雞), a house special, usually requires 24 hours+ advance order, at a cost of $42 per order. One order feeds at least 6 adults with normal appetites.

Despite living in a state with vibrant Vietnamese communities, I still look forward to the Vietnamese food in Toronto, typically with a heavier ethnic Chinese flair. Have been dining here since the 90s when I used to lived in Toronto, and it's still one of my favorites for non-pho options such as bún; and sugarcane shrimp and My Tho noodle soup (not commonly found at Vietnamese restaurants in SoCal) .
Expensive dim sum spot with creative and high quality dim sum.  Over the top (and somewhat gawdy) decor probably from what remained of its predecessor, an Italian restaurant.
AYCE lunch with family and friends. Quality consistent with AYCE standard (low).

10 minutes before closing time (6 pm) on a Sunday night and all my favorite croissants (chocolate and almond) were sold out :((  Ended up with 4 broccoli cheese for half off - must be some kind of end of day discount.
Picking up some croissants to eat later. Convenient place to pick up a croissant or two because it's a chain and has locations throughout the city.
Macarons from a Chinese\/Hong Kong cafe\/bakery?!  Only 3 flavors available (chocolate, green tea, strawberry), @ $3.50 for 2.
There are several Asian Legend locations throughout the city but this one is reputed to be the best one in terms of the taste of the dishes.
Macaron stop #1 on my 2nd day in Toronto, in the pouring rain. It was my favorite macaron place in TO from last year.
One of my favorite markets for health supplements, organic food products and natural beauty products when I Iived in Toronto.
First Vietnamese meal this trip. Torn between Hu Tieu My Tho Kho and Hu Tieu Mi Thap Cam Kho.
Patients who come in complaining of cold\/flu sypmtoms are given face masks to wear to prevent the spread of cold\/flu virus to other patients waiting at the clinic.
Hours on Sundays are from 10:00 am to 3:00 pm. Waiting time to be seen by doctor was less than one hour without appointment (walk-in).

Office visit for ear infection was $58.50 for foreign travelers or non-resident Canadians like me who are not entitled to the Canadian nationalized healthcare system, only about $30 more than my usual co-pay in the U.S. for a PPO type plan that costs over $10,000 in annual premium for the family.
Doing indoor dining because it's raining hard outside :(  At least it's authentic Greek - because we are in...Toronto!!!
Getting some Montreal style bagels with my husband, who prefers good bagels over good macarons.
Per my friends who are locals in Toronto, the best place for rustic Italian dishes - a hidden gem in East York. Closed on Mondays and Tuesdays.
Dermalogica, SkinCeuticals and Babor products are used here for skin treatments.

Had a very relaxing and enjoyable 60 minute Essential Signature Massage by massage therapist Stefenia on 12\/31\/14. She had the right touch and applied adequate pressure on where I needed it the most. Unlike the U.S., massage therapists are licensed AND registered in Canada. Did not get to enjoy the spa facilities thoroughly because the spa closed early on New Year's Eve.
Best location for girls' clothes 7 and up, with lines such as Armani Junior and Scotch R'Belle, on sale now at 50% off with an additional 30% off clearance.

Register to participate in special activities such as the 400 ft zipline, 40 ft rock climbing wall and adrenaline jump, in Ontario's Celebration Zone during the Pan Am Games from July 10 to August 16, 2015, courtesy of Ontario Tourism.

Fill out the online waiver agreement available at http:\/\/treetoptrekking.com\/en\/stouffville\/events\/ontario-celebration-zone\/ to minimize your wait to register fir the rock climbing and ziplining activities. now on to the end of the Para Pan Am Games on 8\/16\/15. Zipliners and adrenaline jumpers must be at least 9 years old, 4'7" tall and between 44 to 250 lbs. There is no minimum age or height for rock climbing but participants must be between 44 to 250 lbs.

Plain Chinese congee\/rice porridge and condiments seem to be regular items at the breakfast buffet but certain items change daily.  Market vegetables not available today, and smoked salmon was added, which was not available yesterday.

Buffet style breakfast ($22.00 per adult; $11.00 per child), includes market vegetable choices such as yellow carrots, asparagus and broccolini for veggie lovers, in addition to the standard items such as eggs, bacon and sausage. A more unusual choice is plain congee (Chinese rice porridge) with traditional condiments such as chopped green onions, peanuts, pickled and spiced vegetables and bamboo shoots.
Other than sushi, robatayaki items are served here. Make sure you ask for the robata bar at the time of reservation. No parking on Adelaide Street before 6:30 p.m. on most days.

We walked in 35 minutes before closing (because there was nothing else my daughter wanted in the area that was still open), and served Annie T. happily took our orders, and didn't make us feel hurried at all. One of the most pleasant servers I have yet to come across.

If you're visiting from the U.S. and happen to be in the area late in the evening looking for a place to grab a quick bite, and want something other than U.S. chains like McD, Chipotle and Five Guys, give this old Canadian chain a try. I am not usually a fan of fries but the fresh cut fries here have me hooked when I have a craving for fries. My 11 year old always request to eat here at least once whenever we are in town for a visit.
Wifi, normally about $15\/day, is free for Starwood Preferred Guest (Platinum). Wifi connection is strong and fast.
Pack Light, Stay Fit" option is very reasonable - New Balance clothing and shoes delivered to your room for only $5.25 for the duration of your stay (NOT daily charge).

Smoked meat here is from a supplier in Montreal. Pastrami, however, is made from scratch in house using brisket meat. Out of all places visited for smoked meat in the city (Caplansky's, Centre Street Deli and Pancer's, Yitz's), husband likes this one the best. Husband (born\/bred in NYC) was also impressed with the pot to table pastrami here.

Restaurant has been around since the 70s. Per current owner Barry, who purchased the business in 2000 from the late Yitz Penciner (original owner and Toronto's deli legend), he kept the old menu, added a few more items and changed the recipe on only one item (gefilte fish).
Restaurant was open as of 6\/25\/17. Great location and view but food is just ok, definitely nothing to write home about.

In addition to being home to the highest courts in the province and to the Law Society of Upper Canada, Osgoode Hall also houses the Great Library, often referred to as "the most beautiful room in Canada." The library serves the needs of legal professionals and law students, and is open to the public. For tourists who intend to tour inside the buildings, it's best to leave at the hotel items that may not pass through a mandatory security check.

The place is more than just a mere tacky and oudated bargain center to those of us who grew up in the city. It's an iconic landmark. If you have vivid memories of the cheesy commercials of the store from the 80s, and you have since moved away, your last chance to pay your final respect is December 30, 2016.
Back here again after one year at this fun place. It makes its exclusive line of ice cream available only at its one and only location, here in Toronto.

The mall has gone through a lot of changes since I first started coming here in its newly opened phase in 1997. Most of the businesses I frequented are long gone or has changed ownership, and there really isn't anything of interest for me to buy anymore (other than drinks at Presotea), but it still holds a lot of memories for me and I like coming here for old time's sake.

Pulled tea (teh tarik) here is amazing - strong tea flavor yet smooth. Foodwise, I find the food a bit over seasoned - peanut sauce was very sweet; assam laksa was very salty even before the optional side of shrimp paste was added. Decor is much nicer than Gourmet Malaysia but I prefer the food at GM.

No luck in convincing the chef to specially make an off menu item (roti tisu) for me. According to our server, roti tisu is only made specially for owner's friends. Must bring my friend (who is a friend of the original owners) with me next time.

Didn't even get a chance to go there for one last order of my favorite Buffalo chips since my high school days in the 80s! Owner stated in a Toronto Star article he may reopen "at another location in Toronto...sooner than you think," but it just won't be the same. All those sweet memories of Mr. Greenjeans being the cool hangout for teens in the 80s, and somewhere in the distance, I can hear Alphaville's Forever Young playing...

Macaron stop #2: The macarons here were not as good as Rahier's when I was in Toronto last year. Here to give it a 2nd chance. Also, Rahier doesn't have lavender macarons and it's available here (one in a pre-packaged box of six).
British sweets galore! Bassetts Jelly Babies, Rowntree Jelly Tots, Jacob's Orange Club (favs from my childhood), as well as other goodies from Barratt, Cadbury and Nestle.

For out-of-town visitors who don't own skates or didn't bring them, skate rentals are $10 for adults, and $5 for kids 12 and under, for 2 hours, with a valid photo ID (no TTC passes or student cards).
Great tool before purchasing your tickets, to see if you should spend extra $$ for better visibility - the Canadian Opera Company's "virtual" seating map at http:\/\/www.coc.ca\/SeatingMap.aspx
Remember you cannot skinny dip by the nude beach because the waters are federally owned. Bring your swimwear if you decide to go in the water.
Very disappointed that there is no separate kosher aisle :((  However, there is a large section of Asian, South Asian and Caribbean section.

As with its sister restaurant (Casa Imperial), Casa Victoria does not offer early bird discounts, though frequent diners may receive 10% off or have tea charge waived by the manager. Vibe is less pretentious than Casa Imperial, with food quality and taste better than Casa Imperial imho. Go for the scallop squid roll wrapped in seaweed (帶子紫菜墨魚燒賣) and other unique dim sum varieties not offered at other restaurants.

Instead of the usual banquet menu, we went with the king crab set dinner for Dad's birthday celebration, at a "special price" of $1,300 if you pay cash PLUS the usual taxes. We hope the restaurant reported the entire $1,300 cash "deal" (plus the $100+ extra for a couple of dishes and longevity peach buns added for our party of 14) to the government and paid 100% of the taxes we paid.
Follow the signs for arrivals to get to the car rental returns area.
All tea drinks are hand shaken. Options such as less sweet (70% less sugar), half sweet (50% less sweet) and unsweetened, less ice and no ice, are available.
Everyone in our party is getting ice cream (from The Kawartha Dairy Company) or Dippin' Dots. I  just noticed the macarons section with signs stating "macaroons." :\/
Didn't think much of this Canadian chain when I used to live here. Here now with my American husband and daughter for my husband's 1st time.  Fries are made from fresh cut (non-frozen) potatoes.
Dinner with cousins in Unionville.

I'm not much of a meat eater but my Jewish husband, a big time carnivore loves the smoked meat here, especially ordered fatty. The cabbage borscht on the menu helped settle the disagreement between husband and myself that borscht does not have to be made with beets! Matzo ball soup here wasn't the best and kreplach is not on the menu, but it's still my husband's favorite kosher style deli in Toronto!
I usually come for the chocolate. Macarons and other pastries were beautiful to look at, but not spectacular in terms of taste and texture.

Went there twice during my 2 week visit this summer. Excellent tea quality, attentive service and refined dim sum that's easy on the tummy. I wish there were more vegetarian varieties but the few that were on the menu were well executed and aesthetically pleasing.
Special promotion on now until 8\/5\/13 - $20 off if you spend $80 or more pre-tax, in addition to 30% off all clearance merchandise in store.

Family dinner at my favorite Quebecois French restaurant.  Steak au poivre is as good as it was in its original location.  So children frendly that it even has a separate menu for children under 12 (with at least 4 entree choices too).

A Jamaican friend introduced this take-out joint to me in the 90s, and I've been hooked ever since. Even after moving away, I still return for a meal or two when I'm back in Toronto for a visit. Favorites include jerk chicken, curry chicken and spicy beef patties. Too bad the chicken fricassee I had back in the day disappeared from the menu. Owners were Hakka Chinese from Jamaica, and it looks like their son (?) is running the business now (or it was sold to another Chinese Jamaican family).
Big things are coming...a new takeout and casual dine-in Nicey's is opening by Markham and Finch.

Food is nothing to get excited over here (low quality meat, sloppy preparation that the crusts were left uncut on the sandwiches), though I feel nostalgically attached to this once popular hangout for HK high schoolers in the mid to late 80s. Even the décor hasn't changed much since the 80s, despite one or several possible ownership changes.

Restaurant owned by the founder of the original Dickens Cafe, a Hong Kong style cafe in Richmond Hill. As a result, one is better off to stick with HK style cafe classics like curries, as opposed to other dishes that try too hard to be real "western" dishes but failed. Hong Kong style "borscht" soup was made much too sweet here.

Used to patronize this Taiwanese grocery at its original location on Steeles for Taiwanese groceries including tapioca pearls (boba - before there were known safety issues). These days, my favorite finds here include A-Sha packaged dry noodles (Hakka spicey variety) and the Taiwan-made Suein (穗瑩) house slippers - so comfortable, light, and free of the chemical odor from China-made ones.
This business is labelled Indian but it actually serves Sri Lankan food and owners are Sri Lankan. Best store bought hoppers I've tasted - available in plain, egg or milk varieties.
Restaurant will serve its last lunch of the year on 12\/19\/14, and re-open again on 1\/6\/15. So much for my plans to have lunch with my daughter there during the holidays. :-(
Restaurant is currently closed for the summer season (2015) and will resume on September 9.

Visitors to Toronto, don't miss the opportunity to experience this well hidden gem where judges and legal professionals dine, in a classically decorated dining area with its walls surrounded by law books. Do keep in mind that you have to go through security to reach the restaurant as it is located inside Osgoode Hall, the building that houses the highest courts of the province. It's open only for lunch during work weeks, and closed for a few months in the summer and a few weeks around Christmas.

Name says China but definitely more Hong Kong-ish (as is the rest of Toronto although the mainlanders' influence has been growing stronger each year). Stores here have wacky hours. It's 12:30 pm and Fruit Jungle is still not open. Now back to Pacific Mall across the street.

Any Italian restaurant that serves bottarga gets my business. This one does it even better by having it on its regular pasta menu, and serving it with wonderfully textured fresh made pasta and pieces of anchovies. Anchovy heaven!

I have not been a resident of Toronto since 1999 but each time I visit, I do my best to make it here at least once or twice because: (1) there is no place that offers this type of dessert in SoCal (my current residence), (2) there is no place in GTA and nearby that offers my two favs here, taro & yam sago delight (芋香蕃薯西米露) and purple sticky rice with taro and small mochi balls (香芋紫米小丸子).
General pricing may be a bit higher than other Chinese supermarkets like Foody Mart nearby but the stores are cleaner with a bigger and better and selection than others in the city.
Late night iced Hong Kong milk tea for me and fruit and bubble tea drinks for the kids. Same owner as the original one in Market Village.

One of very few if not the only place open for breakfast on a weekday morning in the food court area. Breakfast combos are reasonably priced and do the job when you need to eat on the run early in the morning and prefer something Asian over McDonald's. Hong Kong egg-shaped waffles are served here, in addition to the usual HK cafe style dishes.
Icy fresh fruit drinks are tasty and the curry fish balls are comparable to the authentic fare served in the streets of Hong Kong. Yummy!!
Trying to eat enough of these (mini egg waffles) before we return to California!! Not as good as Hong Kong's but definitely better than LA's.
Can't get authentic Hong Kong egg waffles like these in L.A. (not even in the San Gabriel Valley area). Really took it for granted all those years growing up here.

While I love macarons and Cake Opera makes some of the most beautifully shaped ones, its cupcakes are much better in terms of taste. It uses Italian meringue buttercream frosting - less sweet and more rich and smooth than the standard buttercream frosting.

Just received a public email from Alexandria Pellegrino, the "Artist" of Cake Opera, on CO's Facebook page, that she will be teaching and training abroad in the coming year, and no longer taking custom cake orders.
Couldn't resist making a stop again this year. Nicole Ritchie's wedding cake was made by these artisans. A very basic wedding cake starts @ $1,000 and most wedding cakes average about $2,200.
Brewed teas (served hot or iced) are made with Numi tea bags.

HK Chinese owned business with mostly Japanese servers. Crepes and ice cream from the roasted green tea crepes set are very good with a prominent houjicha taste, though I could probably do without the two overly sweet mini chocolate lava cake like brownies.

Back in the 80s, my uncle from Belgium would bring to us a ballotin each time he visited. Glad to see these reasonably priced Belgian truffles so easily attainable nowadays in North America, and still so very good. If you like milk chocolate and butter cream, go for the Lingot milk, my long time favorite.
$10 parking charge on a Saturday (good for all day parking, until the next day @ 6:00 a.m.) is refunded on your restaurant bill when you show your parking stub.

Macaron stop #5 this trip. Great selection of my favorite tea\/floral flavors (Earl Grey; lavender; matcha; rose berry) @ $27 for 12. Probably the best of all 10 macaron shops I have tried in TO between last and this summer - perfect in presentation, texture and taste.
Decoding the flavors: Secret Garden=rose berry; Energy Boost=banana orange.

As in most patisseries in Toronto which carry macarons, the girl behind the counter was able to properly pronounce "macaron" (with the proper French accent too) - much better than the "macaroons" I hear too often in the U.S.

One of very few places opened on Christmas day. Hava nagila was playing when we were there. :-) Service was great, if a bit slow. Great menu for pescartarians - sfiha (fish kebabs), grilled whole fresh catch of the day (branzino on day of our visit), Chilean sea bass masabaha, etc. Paella contains chicken and was a bit too "wet" for my liking.
Restaurant is participating in Winterlicious 2015 (Jan. 30 to Feb. 12). Not sure if it's a good or bad thing for the restaurant....

Found out from my friend Jenny W. that Roti Tissue\/Tisu (cone shaped thin roti usually eaten as dessert, but served as appetizer here) is available though not on the printed menu. Tried ordering at lunch but was told the restaurant could not accommodate it during its busy lunch hours. :\/ Will have to try my luck next time.
$10 minium required for credit card payment.
Unlike most Malay restaurants I have come across in California and New York, you actually hear Malay spoken amongst the staff, and the entire menu is certified halal.
Pricey, high-end dim sum place offers creative varieties. Taste and quality, however, fell below the standard of other dim sum restaurants in the same price range.
Full dairy and sushi menu, and kosher of course (as is almost everything if not everything at this plaza).

Dim sum at this location is more refined than the one at Harbourfront. Dim sum for 6 adults and a 12 year old child came to about $165 after a 10% VIP discount was applied, a bit on the expensive side. High tea quality, refined selection of dim sum and minimal (if at all) use of MSG would be reasons to return. This is also another favorite of my parents who live locally in Toronto.

Revisited this library on 7\/17\/15 after many years of absence since the days when I worked as a page during my high school years. Very little remained unchanged save for the Hebrew book and media section for both adults and children.

Limited seating per night so call in advance to reserve (way in advance if you want sushi bar seating), and make sure you do not arrive later than the scheduled time. Your reservation will not be honored if you show up beyond the reserved time.

Thanks to my Yelp buddy Tetsuro P.'s recommendation, we included an omakase dinner at Kabuto as part of our itinerary for our trip to LV last month.  It made #3 on this list: http:\/\/lasvegasweekly.com\/dining\/2013\/dec\/27\/weeklys-food-editor-picks-most-memorable-meals-his\/
They carry about 6 to 8 varieties of SOMA chocolate bars here.
Owners on vacation - restaurant closed from July 1-20, 2015. :-(

This is the only Congee Queen location I've been to, and one that I visit yearly when I am in town, as this is the location of choice for my parents (who live locally). Really like that it has a good selection of items for everyone, from BBQ items, congee, fried rice and noodles with interesting ingredients, to my favorite soup noodles. We've had no issues with wait since someone from our party usually shows up early before the lunch rush.

I usually visit this shop if I happen to be in Greektown for other reasons. This is not my favorite Leonidas store in the city because it sells too much non-Leonidas goods and its stock of Leonidas chocolates and truffles is quite small and incomplete. Sorbet was too sweet for my liking.
No more Lingot??!! Floranger (orange blossom dark) will have to do.
Checking out The Lord of The Rings sets with our 8 year old daughter. She loves The Hobbit and The Lord of The Rings!

Stairs outside of the cathedral are still in a state of disrepair, the cathedral is still closed and remained in its incompleted state. However, it's nice to see the crumbling mosaic from two years ago restored to its former glory.
Beautiful Slovak Byzantine Rite Cathedral - few scenes from one of my favorite movie "In the Mouth of Madness" was filmed with the cathedral as a backdrop!!
Getting some Hong Kong mini egg waffles for myself and the kids. This place also carries many different types of Chinese snacks and sweets.

For travellers outside of Canada (esp. from the U.S.) who are unfamiliar with TIm Hortons - you must try the honey glazed crullers because you can't find crullers with such soft and airy centers like these!
This place is really a Sri Lankan establishment, even though it's described as serving both Sri Lankan and Indian food. The hoppers here are really good - available plain, milk and egg.

This is probably my #2 spot (#1 being Spring Villa, as of July 2013) for dim sum in Toronto\/York regions. Less high end and less expensive than Casa Imperial, but the creative varieties (mini pot pies of diced chicken w\/ conch in Portuguese sauce, shrimp wrapped w\/ egg white dumplings, pan fried Hakka pork belly buns, etc.) are tasty and beautifully made. Check out my 68 pics taken from 3 dim sums and 3 dinners eaten in a course of 2 weeks.

I don't live in Toronto anymore, but do visit at least once a year. My parents are regulars for dim sum and dinner here, notably the Peking duck, double boiled winter melon soup (both require advance reservation), and various fresh (live) seafood dishes. The lettuce wraps and crispy shells served with the Peking duck are interesting substitutes to the boring flat wrap or bun served with Peking duck at most restaurants in the U.S.

This is probably my #2 spot (#1 being Spring Villa) for dim sum in Toronto\/York regions. A little less high end than Casa Imperial, but the creative varieties (mini pot pies of diced chicken w\/ conch in Portuguese sauce, shrimp wrapped w\/ egg white dumplings, pan fried Hakka pork belly buns, etc.) are tasty and beautifully made. Check out my 68 pics taken from 3 dim sums and 3 dinners eaten in a course of 2 weeks.

This is probably my #2 spot (tied with Casa Imperial, #1 being Spring Villa) for dim sum in Toronto\/York regions. A little less high end than Casa Imperial, but the creative varieties (mini pot pies of diced chicken w\/ conch in Portuguese sauce, shrimp wrapped w\/ egg white dumplings, pan fried Hakka pork belly buns, etc.) are tasty and beautifully made. Check out my 68 pics taken from 3 dim sums and 3 dinners eaten in a course of 2 weeks.

This is probably my #2 spot (tied with Casa Imperial, #1 being Spring Villa) for dim sum in Toronto\/York regions. A little less high end than Casa Imperial, but the creative varieties (mini pot pies of diced chicken w\/ conch in Portuguese sauce, shrimp wrapped w\/ egg white dumplings, pan fried Hakka pork belly buns, etc.) are tasty and beautifully made. Check out my 68 pics taken from 3 dim sums and 3 dinners eaten in a course of 2 weeks.
Non-early bird, regular pricing for dim sum: $3 (S), $4.2 (M), $5.2 (L), $6.8 (XL), and $7.8 (SP).

This is probably my #2 spot (tied with Casa Imperial, #1 being Spring Villa) for dim sum in Toronto\/York regions. A little less high end than Casa Imperial, but the creative varieties (mini pot pies of diced chicken w\/ conch in Portuguese sauce, shrimp wrapped w\/ egg white dumplings, pan fried Hakka pork belly buns, etc.) are tasty and beautifully made. Check out my 68 pics taken from 3 dim sums and 3 dinners eaten in a course of 2 weeks.

Lunch for two on 06\/12\/17 came to CAD$564.10 (USD$420), which included 2 non-alcoholic drinks, tax and gratuity. The ambiance, experience, food and service were all memorable, and well worth the $200+ per person charge. If you are not familiar with Japanese dining etiquette or the kaiseki experience, no question is too small for Kai (assistant manager, host, also the son of owner\/chef) to answer.

One of two hotels in the city that offers afternoon high tea service on weekdays. The Nutcracker High Tea for the holidays is served from 12\/2\/14 to 1\/4\/15, and available in 3 menus (regular @ $42, kids @ $25, or vegetarian @ $42). Reservations are taken with a credit card hold, with a 48 hour cancellation policy.

High" tea here is actually "low" tea served on low tables and sofas. Foodwise, loved the lobster brioche and the untraditional scones (similar to those served in Hong Kong). Service can be spotty and a bit confusing.

My mother swears by this place for Cantonese style BBQ pork. If you speak to the owner\/workers there in Taishanese, you may even get free samples to try before buying. ;-) Whole roast goose now available for $28.00, if you like that sort of thing.

Owner\/chef Sheridan Su, formerly of Great Bao, has a very impressive resume, which includes having worked at Joël Robuchon at the Mansion, Social House (sous chef), and Comme Ça at The Cosmopolitan (executive chef). He has been named as 1 of 5 nominees (with big names such as Ho Chee Boon of Hakkasan, Kim Canteenwalla of Honey Salt) by the editors of Eater Las Vegas for Chef of The Year.
Follow Fat Choy LV on Facebook to find out what the daily specials are.

We were fortunate to have had the opportunity to dine here last month. Fat Choy made it to #10 on this list: http:\/\/lasvegasweekly.com\/dining\/2013\/dec\/27\/weeklys-food-editor-picks-most-memorable-meals-his\/
Fat Choy made it to Eater Las Vegas' The 38 Essential Las Vegas Restaurants for January 2014.

As of 7\/22\/16, the following Canada Post Star Trek 50th Anniversary merchandise sold out elsewhere were still available at this location's postal counter: 2-Stamp Souvenir Sheet Animated Stamps ($10); Original Series Stamp Booklet ($19.95); Stamp Coil Dispenser ($5.95); Set of 8 Official First Day Covers ($22). They make great easy to carry souvenirs for your Trekkie friends back in the U.S.

Expect a wait for large groups especially on weekends or summer weeknights. Took my parents and kids here - kids loved it but parents thought the portions were small for the price, for something they feel they could make at home. That's what they call the generation gap. ;-)

My local friends come mainly for the Hainan chicken rice plate, but I actually find the shrimp in Maggi sauce (Set Lunch menu #217) and baked chicken in Portuguese sauce over rice (Western Dishes menu #W12) decent.

My sister who lives in Toronto took me for a quick dinner here. I thought the service was actually ok, despite my sister's warning to expect rude service. Food was a bit on the salty side but still good overall, and definitely much better than most if not all Hong Kong style cafes we are used to having in SoCal.
If you are from the U.S. and like Red Mango (certain states only) and Pinkberry, you may find this too sweet and not creamy enough. My Canadian niece, who has a very sweet tooth, loved it.
Two seating times for dinner, from Mondays to Sundays, at 6:00 p.m. and 8:30 p.m. Two seating times for weekend lunch, at 11:30 a.m. and 2:00 p.m. No specific seating times for weekday lunch.

Canadian shoe designer most famous for his funky designs. I still remember vividly his first store on Queen Street West in Toronto, which opened in 1989. Most if not all shoes have leather linings and leather soles, and are made in Portugal.
Current (non-early bird) regular pricing as of July 2016: S ($3), M ($4), L ($5), XL ($6), SP ($8), J ($9.80).

This one of my parents' current favorite restaurants for dim sum, dinner and banquet. Notable dishes include 
double boiled winter melon soup (must be reserved in advance) and Peking duck.

Felt a little out of touch with the tea scene in Toronto and nearby towns\/cities since my last visit 15 months ago, and took a local friend's suggestion to try this Taiwanese tea shop. Was disappointed that sakura sencha (纓花綠茶) and Formosa oolong (東方美人) were both out on 10\/8\/14, but roasted milk tea was pretty good. Customization available for amount of iced used and level of sweetness.
First Chinese establishment I first came across this trip that takes credit card payment without a minimum charge. Yes!!
Restaurant is located at an obscure, hidden part of the Tropicana Marketplace, facing Jones Blvd.
If you are from Hong Kong or Macau, the Mozambican curries here may remind you of the taste of the "Portuguese Sauce" dishes you have had in HK or Macau.
Free delivery for orders of $20 and above.

One year old high end dim sum (décor-wise, price-wise, and food-wise in terms of presentation and somewhat in terms of preparation) restaurant with a mainly non-Asian customer base probably due to its location. The chef is the former chef at Lai Wah Heen and some of the wait staff came from Casa Imperial (Scarborough). Other than the noodle rice rolls with thicker than desired skin, everything was generally more refined and less oily than dim sum served uptown, with good vegetarian options.
Tea charge is $2 per person - same pricing for adults and children. Tea quality is considerably higher than the standard dim sum restaurants in the city.
Dim sum pricing as of July 2015: Small ($3), Medium ($4), Large ($5), XLarge ($6), Special ($8).

Seating area seemed a bit bigger than the Scarborough location if the purpose of your visit is to chill with friends over cups of teas as opposed to grab and go. Sakura sencha, out at the Scarborough location the night before, was available here, and as good as the best cup I had in LA (Oh My Pan in San Gabriel, CA). So far, my favorite Taiwan tea shop in GTA and surrounding regions!
Stop by for some award winning Hong Kong milk tea, delicious authentic Hong Kong style curry fish balls and beef balls, and contribute to a good cause.
Most pastries sold here, including the macarons, are from Rahier Patisserie on Bayview Avenue in Leaside.

Seven month old restaurant owned and run by native Japanese from Shizuoka. Seating area is small, which seats about 30 people maximum. Menu appeals to Japanese palates, so taste is delicate and portions are on the small side small. Osechi ryori for the new year, priced at $200 + tax (and $20 + tax charge for a 2-tiered box measuring 7.68" x 7.68" x 4.72"), may be pre-ordered up to 12\/20\/14, and picked up between 3-6 pm on 12\/31\/14.
Hoppers are served only on Fridays and Saturdays. Call ahead to pre-order and confirm if you want a particular specialty (milk, egg, etc.).

As Tamils make up the majority of Sri Lankans living in Toronto and surrounding regions, most Sri Lankan restaurants in the city serve Tamil style Sri Lankan food. This establishment serves Sinhalese Sri Lankan food that is less common in Toronto.

2016 summer camp for school aged children runs from July 4 to September 2. For full day camps (9am-4pm), you have the option of weekly enrollment for $350 or daily enrollment for $84.00, in which you get to choose specific days you want your child to be enrolled. Half day camps (9am-12pm) are also available.

Dim sum served daily from 8:00 a.m. - 3:30 p.m. Non-early bird pricing daily from 11:00 a.m.: $2.80 (S), $3.80 (M), $4.80 (L), $5.50 (XL), $6.50 (SP), $7.50 (J). Chef's special selection not available during early bird hours. Early bird pricing of $2.80 applies only to S, M and L varieties.

Great place for someone (like me!) who loves noodles but prefers fish broth over pork, chicken or beef broth, made without MSG. As with most Chinese restaurants in the area, this is a cash only place that accepts debit cards but not credit cards.

In order to secure a table that seats 8 for the 7 of us, the only option we had was the chef's tasting menu for $65\/pp on a Friday night. Food was just ok - so fusionesque that no hint of Hakka cuisine was left. Chef was accommodating to our special dietary needs (no nuts for half; no pork for the other half) but too many dishes were deep-fried and served with too much thick sauces for my liking.

Dining area is quite spacious unlike traditional Chinese\/dim sum restaurants, as it took over the space of what used to be Fish House. Decor is a bit gawdy, and has a "Guangzhou feel" to it (quoting Jennifer K.). Food was mediocre at best and for the same price range dim sum restaurants, I would much prefer Spring Villa or Dragon Boat.

There is no listing for Presotea on Markville Shopping Centre's store directory. It's located on the second floor, 2 doors from Ten Ren's Tea, and shares a single unit space, ordering counter and cashier with Yogen Früz. As with other Presotea locations, there is no minimum charge for payment by credit card.

Small Chinese shopping center with businesses ranging from the usual bakery, Chinese bookstore, Chinese herb stores, electronics and computer accessories shops, candy\/snack shop, hair salon, lingerie shop, optical store, acupuncturist, esthetician, florist, massage therapist, optometrists, tailors, travel agents, to something as random as a store for house slippers.
Our new spot for fresh king crab, now that mom and dad no longer like Fishman Lobster Clubhouse (魚樂軒). Corkage fee if you bring your own wine is $10.

Waffle cones\/bowls are made on premises - good but not as good as Old Firehall Confectionery's (Unionville). Double scoops on waffle cone or waffle bowl for four people came to a drop over $30 after taxes.

I've been to Dutch Dreams at its original\/present locations a total of 3\/ 4 times and have never had to wait in line, probably because I went during the week at non-peak times (early afternoon). Sad to see some of the iconic decor (garden gnomes, face of man w\/ blue hat, etc.) from the original location missing at its current location, but happy that the seating area is less cramped w\/ more natural lighting in the new location.

Matcha cheesecake coming soon in August. Until then, this side is still a great place to pick up a madeleine, slushy or soft cream (soft serve ice cream) with little wait in case you decided to give up on the line next door, or if you came with someone who is holding the line for you next door.

Waited about 1 hour 20 mins on a Friday evening (@7:30 p.m., 7\/24\/15, Pan Am Games week) for the cheesecake, because I didn't have luck at the Front Street Foods stall after 2 tries. Was it worth the hype? Maybe not, though it was still a pretty good cheesecake and fun experience with my 11 year old as part of our TO adventure as tourists. I've had my fair share of Japanese cheesecakes before and this was one of the lightest and natural tasting (bland for some).

If you didn't like your first few bites of the cheesecake, give it a second chance after placing it in the refrigerator for 3 hours, for an altered taste and texture. The result may be better or worse depending on your preference but it doesn't hurt to give it a try, right?

Being married to a NY born\/bred Jewish American, I've had my fair share of Jewish fare and frequent Ashkenazi Jewish eateries every year I visit TO w\/ the hubby. It's better than the lacking kosher style deli scene where we live (OC, CA), but not our favorite of similar style restaurants we frequent in Toronto and York Region. Smoked meat was a bit less juicy than what hubby prefers. Liked the not overly sweet cabbage rolls but mom-in-law said it needed to be sweeter. Warm and friendly service.

House made ice cream was surprisingly good and better than the waffles imho - flavors were unique, potent yet smooth and natural, with a decently firm texture. My favorite flavors from my last 2 visits were oolong, Earl Grey, vanilla cardamom, and honey orange blossom (in that order). The Earl Grey in particular was probably the best Earl Grey ice cream I have had anywhere.

Cheesecakes at the Uncle Tetsu stall were completely sold out at 2:00 p.m. on a Tuesday (7\/21\/15). Matcha madeleines were available with no set limit @ $3 a piece, with a buy 3 get 1 free promotion.

Tired of "designer" bags that are worn mainly to flaunt status and impress others? Live for yourself and get something unique and fun here - Olbrish of Germany, by-Lin of The Netherlands, and Neòdesign knitted neoprene bags of Italy.
One of the owners is Japanese and the chef was hired directly from Japan.

Omakase courses are now $70 and $120. The $120 course requires reservation ahead of time, but the $70 one does not, even though it states on the menu that the $70 course can only be served at the sushi bar. Still, you can try your luck and ask if the $70 course may be served at a table if you are eating with a large group, and it is not super busy. Mika, the sweet Japanese waitress is very attentive and helpful!

Little gem in this sea of Chinese or Korean owned and managed Japanese restaurants. As someone from SoCal where there is an abundance of authentic Japanese restaurants, I was pleased with the $70 course omakase and loved the Kyoto style milk tofu. While the sushi may not be absolute top notch using SoCal standards, it is probably one of the better options for this area in terms of freshness and taste. It was a shame that 80% of the diners at the restaurant were having ramen when I was there.

Parking lot immediately adjacent to restaurant is entirely blocked off due to construction, so parking can be a challenge. Try your luck with street parking if the limited spaces in the small section not blocked off are filled, or park at the plaza across at your own risk.

Dim sum quality did not disappoint and as good as I remember Spring Villa's was, though the dim sum menu is comparatively smaller than Spring Villa's. VIP card holders are entitled to 10% off but discount is restricted to non-early bird dim sum and payments by cash.

Patio dining area is great news for diners who want to bring along their fur babies. Menu selection is bigger than better than the original takeout location. Really enjoyed the ackee and saltfish during my last visit.
Great anniversary lunch.
Great cut and trim at a nice price.  Thanks Mike!
Fantastic pizza and desserts.
Great skinny top shelf margarita.  Max is a fantastic bartender!  Delicious guacamole.   Nice job again El Encanto!
Our "go to" for brunch.  It can be crowded but the great ambiance, service and food are definitely worth it.
Fantastic coffee, service and customers!  Blown away by it all.  Screw Starbucks.  This is the joint.
My girlfriend is awesome

Great service!  Dan knows his stuff and will accommodate your busy schedule.  He has proven himself an honest service provider by not doing unnecessary work for me.  Keep your money in the neighborhood and utilize a local business man instead of a corporate thief.  Couldn't recommend Wrench Benders more highly.
Amazing food, ambiance and service.   You owe it to yourself to try this place out.
Very spicy Szechuan pork ramen and a Mango Tango. Sit at the bar to se all of the cooking action!
The frozen margaritas are extra strong and are therefore everything I need in life. And my husband too, I love him.
Chicken Mole, spicy. Yum!
Ask Luke to make you a Thirsty Crow. It has bourbon, ginger, lemons, and fresh mint. Refreshing and delicious.
The chorizo cheddar quiche is amazing! Tastes just like chili with crackers.
Jalapeño, cheddar, bacon quiche. I asked for a side of simple hash browns, and was delighted to find slivered carrots and onions in there giving the potatoes an extra kick.
Ask Luke to make you an Aviator. Absolutely on point.
If you like margaritas but want gin instead if tequila, ask Jake to make you a lime gimlet. It's made from Lux's own in-house lime cordial. Yummy, tart, and super fresh on the palette.
Farmer's egg scramble with a side of hash browns and toast.
Mac n cheese with jalapeño and bacon. Oh. Hell. Yes.
If you love whiskey sours, try the Paper Plane, a fresher, cleaner, and much tastier beverage. More artsy, too...that is a single tarragon leaf floating on top.
Try a gorgeous whiskey peach cocktail created by Titus.
Try the chorizo biscuits and gravy with a side of hash browns.
The Cubano made we want to sip, pause, and dance mambo. Delicious!
I love the Cubano latte!
The egg white omelet sounds healthy but looks delicious! I added bacon to mine.

The chicken and rice soup is amazing! It's as rich and flavorful as a beef based soup, which is rare for typically bland chicken and rice soup. The chicken is tender and the rosemary really pops. I had a cup last night and came back for a bowl for lunch.
Ask Dusty to make you a chocolate martini. My favorite dessert!
Try the crepes huevos rancheros and a pom fizz for brunch.
Added bacon to the triple grilled cheese. Yum!
The shrimp and grits look and TASTE amazing! Cheese and herb flavored throughout. Tastes like an awesome home-cooked breakfast.
Skillet special for 11\/01\/15 brunch is delicious. Potatoes, smoky pastrami, onions, peppers, cheese, and eggs. Just look at that beautiful yolk!
Blue pablano salad with salmon on top. Yum!
We're really enjoying the pork flight, fresh pork rinds, pork shank, and pork\/tomato bruschetta, with a carafe of apple Bellini.
Bruschetta: Eggplant & feta, spicy copa, and smoked salmon. 3 for $10.95!
The red pepper lobster bisque is great!
Great $30 French gel manicure by Kim!
The blue corn tamale has a unique earthy smoky flavor. I love it!
The door is hard to find on purpose. It's an IQ test to only allow certain folks in. :)
The beef brisket nachos are amazingly delicious. If you get a salad, ask for the Ranch dressing. It's cool and fresh...tastes homemade.
The augratin potatoes are tender, melt-in-your-mouth A. May. Zing! Sorry for the partial portion photo...just couldn't help myself.
Calamari is...meh. My favorites are still the BBQ pork empanadas and Cuban cigars.
If you like spicy drinks like I do, try the Mule Kick.
Man, there are some weirdo cocktails on this menu. Adventure time!

What is the point of any business listing existing anywhere if their damn operating hours aren't included in it? 
POST THE HOURS PLEASE.
Even though this shows up on Yelp as a karaoke bar, they do NOT do karaoke.
The chicken "tenders" are actually chicken megaliths, and you must get them.
Batman marathon!
This is now called "Lorena's Cafe".
Again, Yelp gets the hours wrong for yet another place. Wineburger does NOT open at 10am, it opens at 11.
Closed on Mondays.
Roofies galore, you had better be on your guard.
This place is not open anymore.
If you're using the public transport option on google maps, the times they give you for the busses and light rail will be patently wrong every single time. Do not trust.
The info here is wrong, this walgreens doesn't actually open until 8am.
One of the rare patios around the Valley that you can still actually enjoy a cigarette on!
Get the Holy Water.
The address listed here is NOT correct. This building is empty.
Permanently closed.
Check-in offer requires in-store "Romance Rewards" account. If you don't already have one, cashier can create one for you.
This place opens at 11:00, not 10:00 like Yelp says.

It's a Tuesday at 6:30, the hours posted in the window say they are open till 8:00 on weekdays. This is probably the 5th time I've tried to come here to eat only to find it closed for no reason. It's ALWAYS like this!
You don't have to be a hotel guest to dine here :)
no more karaoke

Literally the best tacos I have ever eaten. 
Plus, $1 mimosa refills? Yes, please!
Has gone out of business :(
This is the best breakfast burrito I've ever had in my life.
What are the hours?
Here at 10:00, place is stone cold closed even though it says its supposed to be open at 9.
Happy hour 3-6!
Kirin on tap
Great staff & meeting rooms
If you like scrambled eggs you will like this place, They will not do eggs any other way
You can smell the bacon a block away...
Happy hour until 6:30 half off margaritas
Happy hour 4:30 to 6:30
Premium grade gasoline, the pony likes it
Free peanuts served in a dog bowl, classy!
Parking can be problematic
Russel Shaw is speaking this morning.
Beef and scallops only $13 at lunch! Plus join the birthday club and get $30 off birthday dinner!
$2.95 happy hour specials 3 to 7 pm & 9 to close
Raspberry lemonade is excellent!
Great lunch special pick 2 for $8
Discount coupons on their website
Love this place!
Sunday brunch is incredible,  champagne,  mermosas, skyy bloody marys are included
Have yet to see a dead body...
You can dine in a streetcar
Happy hour 3 to 6
Great happy hour menu 3 to 6!
Peach lemonade perfection
Yes, they do serve kirin and sake

We took the recommendations from Branden {wonderful server}. Different than what we may normally try BUT deeelicious!! We had two rolls (Red Sun and Salmon Screw), Gyoza (8 for $4!) and the seafood hot pot. MORE than enough food and all for under $40 WITH tip! Unbelievable.
Love them all! Gel pedicures!
banbanji. great for summer! sorry ate before shot lol
its just a cvs lol
recently add bunch of new american songs, and upgraded to more user-friendly interdface.
good food. i like the pistachio crusted salmon, especially when ure on diet lol
Draft Beer, mango tango sake, gyoza, summer roll, crunchy roll, caterpillar, rainbow roll, salmon nigiri... For two at happy hour!
Madhouse on Saturday at 1p.
Get lunch at Pane Bianco next door, then get a coffee and pastry\/dessert at Lux.
Gyro bowl, fondue, FEZ burger w\/ bacon, and a Kiltlifter... For two. ~$30 and we're stuffed!
No pour-over coffee here.. But good iced coffee.
Park across the street (next to speedy cash) if you don't want to pay $3 for valet.
Seriously, some of the best scallop nigiri. So fresh!
Strawberry whoopie pie is amazing. Strong strawberry flavor!
One & one = one shot of espresso & one macchiato
Live frogs!!
Hooray for dog friendly outdoor seating!
Menu is supposed to be anti-inflammatory.
$5 glasses of wine and pitchers of beer (~2 beers) everyday before 11a-5p
If you're looking for a medium bodied red, and don't mind kinda spicy.. I really enjoyed the Man Vintners Shiraz (2011 - South Africa)
Perfect place for a late night meal w friends and dogs
Fan of the date night special. 2 entrees, 2 cocktails\/wine\/beer, and 2 desserts. For $20.
Open 7a-6p daily, with Sundays at 7a
Basil Seed Drink, Spring Roll (2), Chicken Curry, Katheaw Cha... For two!
2 spring rolls, chicken curry, Katheaw Cha, Lok Lak Beef.. Dinner feast For two! And leftover lunch!
Tea, coconut juice, guava juice, 3 spring rolls, lok lak beef, amok fish, 2 chicken curries, Katheaw Cha... For four. We're crazy. Crazy stuffed.
Don't trust the Yelp map. It's located on Highland Ave and 7th Ave
Maya tea chai is amazing.
Get a high 5er and give the barista a high five!
2 jars (bacon\/avo + bread pudding) and potato croquettes for two!! Sunday brunch here is amazing! Until 2p every Sunday.
Green curry w tofu and drunken noodles w shrimp... For two! Oh and free green tea ice cream!!
Closed for renovations. =(
Happy hour every day 3-6!!
Don't be mistaken, get a toasted marshmallow!! Amazing.
Love this place. But if you order the sesame beef bowl and sub noodles for the rice, I'd recommend asking for less salt or sauce. It was a bit too salty without brown rice.
Pitbulls and Rottweilers not allowed. Lame.
Closed on Tuesdays!!
Outdoor patio is not dog-friendly.
Great service, good food! Try the shrimp pad Thai or spicy Korean beef noodles. Both generous portions and they don't skimp on the shrimp :)
It's all about the special halo halo!  For $5 topped with ube (taro) ice cream and a piece of leche flan. Yummm!
Nice and cozy inside. Cool!
Very nice inside. Cool menu. Can't wait to order.
Best German Sausage in town.
Check out their website to virtually tour their store. It's like Google Street view inside. Way cool!
Just keep on driving up until you get to the very top. Signage is not very visible and a bit confusing.
Very friendly service with a cool pizza parlor decor inside.
Great place to get items for a Rick Bayless Family Easter Dinner tomorrow. Yummy!
Quick and friendly service. Very helpful in the selection process. Saved $70 with a special they were running on Michelin tires.
They sell beds and lots of them. Trying to find one that will last more than 6 months and still be comfortable. They just don't make them like they used to. Big selection here. Nice!
Cool place for hard to find items that the big box stores do not carry.
I love this Place. Remodeling looks Great!

Just got BUSTED for taking a picture in the store. The food police slapped my hand this time. What is so secret? The store is beautiful. Maybe they should put their small warning sign on the entrance instead of the exit door. LOL or OMG?
This place is probably best for a night of heavy drinking and getting it delivered.
I like the Tatum and Cactus location better. This one always seems mediocre.
This place is huge !!!
Used a 20 percent off coupon and I found on the internet.

They like to close asap, especially on weekends, but lamb vindaloo is awesome at 11 or 1130, any later they called last call...awesome patio!

Now that October is here, the patio late at night is awesome! A huge hoegarten beer and a lamb vindaloo pasty is splendid...don't expect to order any later than 1130ish, as the workers want to go home or out too!  ( cant blame them) same great quality in spite of organizational expansion & restaurant growth!
Very prompt & professional. Great demeanor with excellent advice. Very clean office with just enough decor and technology. Great prices & I'll be back for more work soon.
The best menudo in the valley! Perfect size, texture & flavor. Cheap too! Yes, don't miss pollo adovado burritos...tender marinated  & pure chicken. Get guac on the side if eating later.

Only one entrance\/exit...on to busy university ave. Food\/drinks specials o.k...waitress asked if I needed change on twenty two doll. Tab...gave her forty and asked for ones..how nervy trying to con eighteen dollars!
The ambiance is so authentic, I feel like I am in mexico! Try the buche tacos...don't ask any questions, just try it! Think "pork calamari" and enjoy heaven!

Good concept to serve super spicy options...but, they barely put any meat on the tostadas...probably so you won't burn yourself! To me, this is purely a gimmick to save on meat costs & sell more drinks!
Great burgers, tried new one rolled in freshly milled peppercorns & bacon. Find waitress with good attitude and sit in her section! Packed when cle browns game on...avoid that.

Come before or after busy lunch or dinner time. Very comparable to the 5 or 6 BBQ joints we tried near Austin\/San Antonio.  Brisket is perfect no matter how you like it, pork good but sweet mustard sauce is a little sweet.  Great condiments to set off near perfect lite smoke bbq.!

Angus asada grilled inside over carbon. 5$ even for asada pure meat burro.  All condiments free.  They fold burrito 100% w\/spachula...no manos!  Frijoles Rojas are addicting...I could drink as a beverage...so good!

Excellent, made from scratch wontons in the soup!  A large is only 2.95!  Fast, fresh and rather authentic. Smaller containers now & they are using gimmick of dried noodles under food to give appearance of more food. Fresh, but expensive take out...don't like the new trickery!;

Over 30 flat screens, a gorgeous video wall & A+ servers...food flavorful, but reheated...tried to give me used & smelly to go container...which I refused....should have sought out whoever's idea that was!

Went solo for dinner...goat biryani 13.99 reheated rice w\/scarce meat..served in a medium soup bowl (not taureen or platter)...potato\/cauli agloo in little dish the size of a butter tray 8.99! Threw what little food given into a togo box, paid & left. Owner knocked $5.00 off

Try the tamale smothered on chili with cheese and onions. Not a Mexican tamale, more like a red's tamale! Less than 5.00 & nostalgic for me, as my dad loved red's & he grew up in Chicago. Don't compare to the mex version, this is different\/good!
